JOHANNESBURG - One of the country's top forensic pathologists has dismissed suggestions that mortuary assistants get to perform autopsies.Professor Gert Saayman is the chair of the national forensic pathology service committee.READ: Army called in as bodies pile up at mortuariesHe says only medically-trained pathologists are responsible for post-mortems.While their assistants only help with cleaning, cutting and sewing bodies among others.Forensic officers in Gauteng have been on a go-slow for nearly a month now.READ: Court orders autopsies as mortuary strike continuesThey say they're called upon to perform functions that are above and beyond their pay-grade.The strike has caused massive backlogs, with families struggling to bury their loved ones.Health unions and the Gauteng government reached a deal to end the ongoing strike by mortuary workers on Wednesday. 